{"title":"Coherency Improved Explainable Recommendation via Large Language Model","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Multitask explainable recommenders often produce incoherent outputs where the generated textual explanation does not align with the predicted rating, since explanations are not explicitly conditioned on the rating.","method":"CIER uses a pipeline with an LLM backbone (LLaMA2-7B fine-tuned via LoRA) to first predict a soft rating distribution using a verbalizer over tokens {'1'...'5'}, then embeds this distribution into the LLM word embedding space via SR2WE (a weighted sum of the embeddings of the rating tokens). The explanation generator then conditions on user/item info and this rating embedding to produce rating-aware explanations, trained in a pipeline manner akin to next-token prediction. Ablations show that removing rating-aware conditioning or SR2WE degrades explainability and text quality, confirming the benefit of explicit rating conditioning."},{"problem":"Coherence between ratings and generated explanations is hard to evaluate at scale; prior automatic metrics rely on manually annotated data or bespoke classifiers, which are costly and limit reproducibility.","method":"The paper proposes an annotation-free automatic coherence evaluation using public models: GPT-4 (gpt-4o) is prompted to judge whether an explanation matches a given rating, and a BERT-based sentiment classifier (bert-base-multilingual-uncased-sentiment) predicts a sentiment rating for each explanation. Coherence is measured as the proportion of cases where the sentiment rating is within ±1 of the model’s rating. This framework is applied to all models and correlates with human judgment, showing CIER achieves higher coherence than baselines."},{"problem":"Explainable recommenders struggle to capture salient item features in explanations (low explainability) and face a train–inference mismatch when training on hard labels but inferring with soft rating distributions.","method":"CIER introduces two training techniques: (a) a curriculum learning strategy with an auxiliary keyword generation task that gradually transitions to full explanation generation via a linear schedule, helping the model first learn salient features then compose complete explanations; and (b) rating smoothing that spreads probability mass only to neighboring ratings, leveraging rating ordinality and better matching the soft distribution used at inference. Experiments show curriculum learning outperforms vanilla and two-stage training, and ablations indicate removing rating smoothing reduces FMR/ROUGE across datasets."}]}
